Java Lock (java.util.concurrent.locks.Lock) does guarantee the lock gaining order.
I see two issues with the code in the question. That is why it is not demonstrating the expected results.

 1. The &quot;same&quot; lock object should be used to lock the threads. In the code, it creates new Lock object for each Thread, use that object to take the lock.
 2. The threads will not invoke the &quot;lock.lock()&quot; line in the same order they invoke the &quot;System.out.println(....&quot; executes before test!&quot;)&quot; line. Thread-1 may execute the &quot;println&quot; line and wait a while, And Thread-2 may execute both &quot;println&quot; line and the &quot;lock.lock()&quot; line. So even though you see, &quot;Thread-1...&quot;, &quot;Thread-2....&quot; in the console, The actual order those threads try to acquire the lock is, &quot;Thread-2&quot;, &quot;Thread-1&quot;.

Below is a code to demonstrate the Thread lock behavior

    public class App {

	public static final int THREAD_COUNT = 20;

	public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {

		Lock lock = new ReentrantLock();

		for(int i=1; i&lt;=THREAD_COUNT; i++) {
			Thread t = new MyThread(lock);
			t.setName(&quot;Thread-&quot; + i);
			t.start();

			/*
			 * give some time to thread &quot;t&quot; to go and lock itself before sending the next thread.
			 * So that threads will be lock in the order of - Thread-1, Thread-2, ...... Thread-19, Thread-20
			 */
			Thread.currentThread().sleep(100);
		}
	}

	static class MyThread extends Thread {

		private final Lock lock;

		public MyThread(Lock lock) {
			this.lock = lock;
		}

        @Override
        public void run() {
        	try {
				System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + &quot; try to pick the lock&quot;);
				lock.lock();
				/* *********************************************************************
				 * Locked threads will be released based on the order they got locked
				 ********************************************************************** */
				System.out.println(&quot;\t\t\t\t&quot; + Thread.currentThread().getName() + &quot; got the lock&quot;);

				/* **************************************************************************
				 * sleep/wait this thread enough time,
				 * so that other threads can come and lock themselves at &quot;lock.lock()&quot; line
				 ************************************************************************** */
				Thread.sleep(2000);

			} catch(InterruptedException ex) {
				ex.printStackTrace();
				Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
			} finally {
				System.out.println(&quot;\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&quot; + Thread.currentThread().getName() + &quot; released the lock&quot;);
				lock.unlock();
			}
        }
    }
}

 - The *Thread.currentThread().sleep(100)* in the *main* method is used to give  the thread &quot;t&quot; enough time to execute both &quot;*println*&quot; line and the &quot;*lock.lock()*&quot; line. So that we see the correct thread locked order in the console
- The *Thread.sleep(2000)* in *MyThread: run* method is used to give enough time for all other threads to come and lock themselves at the &quot;*lock.lock()*&quot; line. (*Even though this delay applies to all the threads, this is necessary for only the first thread*)

