The Spring Framework provides `SyncTaskExecutor` which implements `TaskExecutor` hence `Executor`.
It simply executes the `Runnable` right away

```
	@Override
	public void execute(Runnable task) {
		Assert.notNull(task, &quot;Runnable must not be null&quot;);
		task.run();
	}
```

In order to make all Spring `@Service`s make use of this `Executor` you can provide a `@TestConfiguration` class somewhere in the *src/test/java* folder.

```
@TestConfiguration
public class TestConfig {
  
  @Bean
  public Executor syncTaskExecutor() {
    return new SyncTaskExecutor();
  }
}
```

[@TestConfiguration][1] is very useful for overriding some `@Bean`s only for the scope of test execution. According to its documentation:

&gt; @Configuration that can be used to define additional beans or
&gt; customizations for a test. Unlike regular @Configuration classes the
&gt; use of @TestConfiguration does not prevent auto-detection of
&gt; @SpringBootConfiguration.

After that the test class should be annotated with `@ContextConfiguration(classes = TestConfig.class)`


  [1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/current/api/org/springframework/boot/test/context/TestConfiguration.html

